definition.value: A biome which is subject to tropical climatic conditions.
A biome which is subject to subtropical climatic conditions.
A biome which is subject to alpine altitudinal conditions.
A biome which is subject to montane altitudinal conditions.
A biome which is subject to arid environmental conditions.
A process during which one entity loses energy to another entity.
A material accumulation process during which the volume of liquid entity increases.

value.value: A temperature of air at which air become saturated with water vapour and below which airborne water vapour will condense to form liquid water (dew).
Electromagnetic radidation which involves radiant energy in a spectral range (wave band) between 400 to 700 nanometers, that photosynthetic organisms are able to use in the process of photosynthesis.

label.value: concentration of carbon dioxide in an atmosphere

definition.value: The concentration of carbon dioxide when measured in air that is part of an atmosphere.

value.value: A depression in the ground resembling a hole or cavity, either natural or anthropogenic.
A pit which is used for the collection and storage of manure.
Coastal water is a marine water body bordering a coast.
A mixture of crushed and coarsely ground bones that is used as an organic fertilizer for plants and formerly in animal feed.

definition.value: Food material which can be used to meet nutritional requirements of plants.
Dust which is derived from mineral material.
Dust which is composed primarily of some metallic material.
Dust which is derived from clay material.

value.value: A liquid or a gas.

definition.value: A process in which includes the components of an environmental system as participants.

value.value: A type of land degradation in which terrestrial ecosystem becomes increasingly dry, typically losing its bodies of water as well as vegetation and wildlife.

A general and temporary condition of partial or complete inundation of normally dry land areas from the overflow of inland and/or tidal waters, and/or the unusual and rapid accumulation or runoff of surface waters from any source. A great flow along a watercourse or a flow causing inundation of lands not normally covered by water.

definition.value: A process which occurs within an atmosphere.

value.value: A process which diminishes the functioning of an ecosystem located on land.

definition.value: A process during which humans apply technology to alter the magnitude, duration, rate, or impact of an environmental process.
An environmental process which is driven by the action of humans.

value.value: An action of exogenic processes (such as water flow or wind) which remove environmental material from one part of a planet's crust, transporting it to another location where it is deposited.

definition.value: An environmental process which has water - in any of its states - as a participant.

value.value: Evapotranspiration is the sum of evaporation and plant transpiration from the Earth's land and ocean surface to the atmosphere.

Evaporation is a form of vaporisation which occurs when a portion of the surface layer of a liquid in contact with a gaseous material, which is not saturated with the evaporating substance, vaporises.

definition.value: Transpiration is the process of water movement through a plant and its evaporation from aerial parts of that plant, such as from leaves but also from stems and flowers.

value.value: A physical process during which atoms, molecules, or other consituents of a material entity are forced closer together.

definition.value: A process during which the mass of one or more materials, present within a given site, increases.
A process during which material is displaced from its original location and transported either to a new location or back to the original location.

value.value: A depression which is part of a planetary crust, is of geographic scale, and is partially or completely enclosed.
A material transport process during which one or more environmental materials are transported by the action of wind.
Sediment which has been transported through the marine water column, settling on the seafloor.

definition.value: A material accumulation process during which solid particles are pulled through a water body by gravitation or centrifugal force and which ends when they settle on a solid surface.
A process during which a portion of some environmental material is converted into a different material or a collection of materials.

label.value: desublimation of water vapour into ice

definition.value: A desublimation process during which water vapour is frozen into water ice.
A one-dimensional temporal region which is delimited by the occurrence of processes which serve as its delimiters.
A geographic feature which is primarily composed of a continuous mass of snow and/or ice.
A mass of snow.

value.value: A structure which traverses a mass of one or more environmental materials, and encloses a roughly tubular site.

label.value: concentration of nitrate and nitrite in liquid water

definition.value: The concentration of nitrate and nitrite when measured in liquid water.

value.value: A season during which changes in atmospheric circulation associated with the asymmetric heating of land and sea cause moisture to be brought inland by monsoon winds, leading to increased rainfall as moisture-laden air rises  and cools over land.
A water ice crystal which is constituted by water molecules aligned in a hexagonal array.
Sediment which contains some chemical contaminant.
